<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   French General To Head Forces in Former FRY </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102171094 Paris AFP in English 1633 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0102171094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, Feb 1 (AFP) -- UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali said here Tuesday [1 February] that French 
General Bertrand de Lapresle would be the new chief of UN forces 
in the former Yugoslavia. If confirmed by the UN Security 
Council, he will replace compatriot General Jean Cot at the end 
of March, Butrus-Ghali told a news conference. 
  Paris had proposed de Lapresle as Cot's replacement one week 
ago. France has the largest contingent of troops in the former 
Yugoslavia with 6,000 soldiers. 
  Butrus-Ghali and Cot had disagreed over the general's 
repeated public demands that he be given the authority to order 
use of air support in Bosnia-Hercegovina if he deemed it 
necessary. Butrus-Ghali delegated this authority to his 
civilian representative in Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi of Japan, 
for two operations specific to Srebrenica and Tuzla. 

</TEXT>

