<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Fed Up' UN Human Rights Observer May Resign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302065294 Paris AFP in English 2116 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302065294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Geneva, Feb 2 (AFP) -- Former Polish Premier 
Tadeusz Mazowiecki could resign from his post of UN rapporteur 
on human rights in the former Yugoslavia, an official said here 
Wednesday [2 February]. 
  "I've heard he is fed up," Pieter van Wullften Palthe, 
chairman of the UN Commission on Human Rights told a press 
conference. "We are all disillusioned but I hope it's not a 
reason for giving up," Wullften Palthe said, adding that the 
resignation could be announced during the commission's current 
annual session, which started Monday. 
  Appointed in August 1992, Mazowiecki has prepared several 
reports on human rights abuses in the former Yugoslavia. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

