<F P=100> ALBANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Group Concludes `Partnership' Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302065194 Tirana TVSH Television Network in Albanian 1900 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0302065194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana TVSH Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Albanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A high-ranking NATO delegation has ended its visit 
in our country. Here is a report: 
  [Correspondent] Continuing last evening's talks with the 
high-ranking NATO delegation and after stressing that Albania 
actively supports the Partnership for Peace [PFP] plan, Defense 
Minister Safet Zhulali referred to the letter by President Sali 
Berisha to NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner in which he 
officially expressed Albania's desire to participate in the PFP 
and develop extensive cooperation within NATO. The letter also 
reads: We are ready to work with the political and military 
structures of the alliance, participate in joint military 
maneuvers and consultations on defense and security, and take 
advantage of other possibilities offered by the PFP. We are 
willing to offer a company, as well as our naval and air bases 
for the PFP purposes. Albania is the first ex-communist country 
to have requested NATO membership. Albania's goal continues to 
be membership in the North Atlantic Alliance. 
  The talks concluded that Albania will be prepared to draft 
the position paper and sign the PFP agreement in Brussels. The 
meeting also defined those areas in which Albania commits itself 
to participate, such as joint exercises, peacekeeping and 
humanitarian operations, and the creation of air and port 
facilities. They also agreed that Albania will send its own 
permanent representatives to the relevant NATO institutions. 
  NATO Assistant Secretary General Gebhardt von Moltke stated 
that he was impressed by Albania's performance and its readiness 
to participate in the PFP. We will help to complete the position 
paper and everything else so as to ensure Albania's active 
participation in the PFP plan. He asked our defense minister to 
convey greetings to President Sali Berisha from NATO Secretary 
General Manfred Woerner, as well as his high regard and best 
wishes on the cordial message and Albania's position considering 
PFP participation. 
  The high-ranking NATO delegation left our country this 
morning. Defense Minister Safet Zhulali, Foreign Ministry 
representatives, and high-ranking Defense Ministry cadres were 
at Rinas Airport to see the delegation off. Greek Ambassador in 
Tirana Khristodhoulos Tsalikis was also present. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

