<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus `Angry' Over Austrian Stance on Temelin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202195794 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus expressed alarm 
today about Austria's consistently voiced doubts about the 
completion of the Temelin nuclear power plant construction. He 
pointed out that the Czech Government's stance on this matter is 
final. Our Prague correspondent Daniela Galikova reports in more 
detail: 
  [Galikova] According to Vaclav Klaus, the Czech Government 
does not identify itself with Austrian Chancellor Vranitzky's 
idea of a nuclear-free Europe. However, this does not mean that 
the government denies Austria's right to hold its own view. 
Nevertheless, being the government of an independent state, the 
Czech Government is also entitled to a different view. I am 
angry that Austria does not take seriously the fact that the 
Czech Government's decision on completing the construction of 
the Temelin nuclear plant is final. I do not understand the 
reasons for the debate on not completing the Temelin power 
station or rebuilding it to use gas fuel. 
  [Begin Klaus recording] Why should I continue to write 
letters or issue statements because somebody on the Austrian 
side seems to hold the view that we did not in fact mean our 
decision and that it was a joke by the Czech Government or 
perhaps an attempt to prod our neighbors? This is simply 
untrue. Should I put this in stronger terms or in very strong 
terms? I am simply saying it. [end recording] 
  [Galikova] The Czech prime minister went on to say that the 
entire affair has gone beyond the framework of the present 
Austrian Government's usual attitude toward the completion of 
Temelin. He goes so far as to consider this to be 
inappropriate, especially in the context, which he mentioned, of 
his talks a few days ago with officials from Switzerland and 
Germany, whose nuclear power stations are as close to the 
Austrian border as is Temelin. However, there are no protests 
against them. As regards Austria's attempt to choose whom they 
consider to be a weaker partner and use them as a testing 
ground, I have to say that we are not a weaker partner, Vaclav 
Klaus stressed when speaking in Prague a few hours ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

