<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transformer Fire at Dukovany Nuclear Plant </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302134694 Paris AFP in English 1334 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 3 (AFP) -- A transformer fire Thursday 
morning at the Czech nuclear power plant in Dukovany, in the 
eastern Moravian region, caused no casualties nor radiation 
leaks, the CTK news agency reported. 
  The fire, which broke out shortly after 7 a.m. (0600 GMT) at 
the plant's third reactor, was extinguished two hours later, the 
agency said. 
  Power was maintained at minimal level throughout the 
incident, after initially dropping to 30 percent below minimum 
when the fire broke out, it added. 
  The state of the third reactor had "stabilized" after the 
incident, which was classed as level 0 on the INES international 
scale, according to an expert from the state nuclear security 
office quoted by CTK. 
  The plant, some 40 kilometres (25 miles) north of the 
Austrian border in Moravia, has four 440 megawatt 
ex-Soviet-built VVER [water-moderated water-cooled power 
reactor] reactors. 
  The incident came a day after Czech Prime Minister Vaclav 
Klaus confirmed his country's decision to press ahead with 
building a nuclear power plant at Temelin in southern Bohemia -- 
a project which has been heavily criticized by Austria, which 
fears radioactive fallout from possible accidents. 
  The Temelin plant, to be completed in two or three years at 
a 
site only 40 kilometres from the Austrian border, will have two 
1,000 megawatt ex-Soviet-type VVER reactors. 
  Austria, which has banned nuclear facilities on its 
territory, has asked Prague to build a gas-based plant instead. 
  Klaus said his government's decision was "final" and that 
Austria "should recognize the sovereignty of the Czech Republic." 
  Responding to Klaus's remarks later Wednesday, Austrian 
Chancellor Franz Vranitzky said Vienna would continue its 
efforts to block construction of the plant. 
  A nuclear accident "would not only be a risk for the 
sovereign Czech Republic, but also for the neighbouring 
populations," Vranitzky said, adding that the April 1986 
accident at Ukraine's Chernobyl nuclear plant "was not limited 
to sovereign contamination." 
  Austrian efforts to block the project were undermined last 
Thursday when the American EXIM-Bank decided to guarantee a loan 
needed to complete the Temelin project. Citi-Bank was authorized 
to grant a 317 million dollar loan to the plant's builder, 
Westinghouse. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30396 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu023_c_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-023 </AU>
