<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim-Croat Negotiations on Mostar Collapse </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202144294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1156 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bileca, 2 February (TANJUG) -- Smail Klaric, the 
chairman of the war presidency of the eastern part of Mostar, 
has informed the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] commander in 
former Yugoslavia, General Jean Cot, about the collapse of 
Muslim-Croat negotiations on Mostar. 
  Negotiations on European Union's proposal to proclaim Mostar 
an open city under the protectorate of one of the European 
states lasted for several days in the UNPROFOR base in 
Medjugorje, and they were attended by Owen and Stoltenberg's 
special envoy. 
  Klaric informed General Cot yesterday that the delegation of 
the HVO [Croatian Defense Council] demanded that Mostar be the 
capital of the Croat Republic of Herzeg-Bosna offering that the 
European Union protectorate only be in the part of the city 
currently controlled by the Bosnia-Herzegovina army. 
  The Muslims could not accept this Croat proposal and the 
negotiations broke down, Klaric informed Gen. Cot. 

</TEXT>

