<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urge Lifting of Arms Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202180494 Paris AFP in English 1744 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0202180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Helene Despic-Popovic: "Bhutto, Ciller Demand </F>
Justice for Bosnian Moslems"] 
  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, Feb 2 (AFP) -- Pakistani and Turkish 
Prime Ministers Benazir Bhutto and Tansu Ciller Wednesday [2 
February] called for lifting of the arms embargo on Bosnia and 
urged the govermment to reject any "unjust" negotiated 
settlement to the war. 
  In a joint declaration issued during their brief visit to 
the 
besieged Bosnian capital, the two Islamic heads of government 
said that "rarely has a nation been subjected to such merciless 
savagery in the full view of the world" as had Bosnia. 
  Stressing the humanitarian nature of their high-profile 
mission, Bhutto and Ciller called for the immediate lifting of 
the "unjust" international arms embargo, which "contravenes 
(Bosnia's) inherent right to self-defence." 
  With all-party peace talks on the future of Bosnia set to 
resume February 10 in Geneva amid signs of intensified military 
build-ups by all three sides on the ground, the two leaders 
denounced all attempts to impose a settlement on the 
mainly-Moslem Bosnian side. 
  "Bosnia must not be forced to negotiate at gunpoint," the 
statement said. "We will resist an imposed settlement which 
rewards the aggressor." [passage omitted] 
  Both women -- the most senior politicians to visit Sarajevo 
since French President Francois Mitterrand in June 1992 -- also 
stressed they were opposed to a carve-up of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Bhutto and Ciller, who were given the red-carpet treatment 
and a guard of honour on arrival at Sarajevo airport and for 
whose visit the UN Protection Force imposed tight security 
measures, called in their statement for an end to the siege of 
the capital. 
  They also called for the immediate lifting of all obstacles 
to the delivery of humanitarian aid, and the re-opening of Tuzla 
airport, northern Bosnia, which has been shelled by Bosnian Serb 
troops. [passage omitted] 
  The Bosnian premier was due to take the two leaders on a 
tour 
of the city's main Kosevo hospital. [passage omitted] 
  Izetbegovic said Tuesday his government would reject at 
fresh 
talks any settlement not offering the "just peace" which had so 
far not been forthcoming. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

