<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Receives Prime Ministers Bhutto, Ciller </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202220594 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2100 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202220594 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Croatian President Franjo Tudjman received 
[Turkish Prime Minister] Tansu Ciller and [Pakistani Prime 
Minister] Benazir Bhutto at the presidential palace this 
evening, the president's office said in a statement. 
  Both prime ministers told President Tudjman about their 
impressions after their short visit to Sarajevo and stressed the 
need to establish peace as soon as possible as well as mutual 
trust between the Croats and the Bosnian Muslims in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Turkey and Pakistan will do their utmost for 
this to be achieved. 
  Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto particularly stressed that 
international borders are inviolable, ethnic cleansing 
impermissible, and that the situation must be reestablished as 
it was before the war. 
  Pakistan upholds Croatia's justified demand to have the [UN] 
protected zones reintegrated into its state and legal system. 
She also said that Bosnia-Herzegovina must preserve its 
multicultural and multiethnic character and that the fighting 
between the Croats and Bosnian Muslims should end, as she had 
also told [Bosnian] Prime Minister Silajdzic during their brief 
talks. 
  Turkish Prime Minister Ciller said Turkey is pressing for 
the 
urgent establishment of peace in the area, but that only a just 
solution can be accepted. Continued hostilities will mean that 
the longer they go on the more difficult it will be to reach a 
political agreement, and the foundations for the communal life 
of Bosnian Muslims and Croats will be seriously threatened. 
  At the end of their talks President Tudjman said that the 
Croats and Bosnian Muslims must reach agreement and he proposed 
that both [the Pakistani and the Turkish] prime ministers press 
for a summit of all interested countries with the aim of 
establishing peace, which Benazir Bhutto and Tansu Ciller 
accepted. Turkish Prime Minister Tansu Ciller said her country 
is ready to host such talks, because the establishment of peace 
would be in the interest of the whole of Europe and the world. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

