<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chamber Issues Foreign Policy Conclusions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202174794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0202174794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Chamber of Deputies has adopted the following 
conclusions on Croatian foreign policy: 
  The Chamber of Deputies gives its support to the joint 
declaration signed by the Republic of Croatia and the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia, as a political means for achieving 
lasting peace. 
  The declaration is an important step toward mutual 
recognition of the two sovereign countries, and also paves the 
way for reaching a political solution and for unconditional 
re-integration of the UN-protected areas into the Republic of 
Croatia. The declaration will contribute toward normalizing 
relations between the two states and toward general stability in 
the whole of southeast Europe. An important step on the way is 
explicit recognition of all the states in their legitimate 
international borders. 
  The Chamber of Deputies called on Bosnian Muslims to 
unconditionally and promptly halt attacks on Croat-populated 
areas, in particular in central Bosnia. If they fail to do so, 
the chamber believes that the government and the president of 
the republic should examine the current state of diplomatic 
relations between the Republic of Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The deputies most strongly condemn all crimes and acts which 
are in breach of international law on warfare and humanitarian 
issues, and call on the president and government to do their 
utmost in the diplomatic, political, humanitarian and all other 
fields to guarantee the survival and normal life of Croats in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  All sides in the conflict were called upon to persist in 
their efforts to end the war through negotiation and political 
means and to reach a just and lasting solution acceptable to all 
three peoples. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

