<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canadian Troops Held by `Drunken' Soldiers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302123494 Paris AFP in English 1228 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Feb 3 (AFP) -- Drunken Croatian soldiers 
disarmed four Canadian UN troops and held them for an 
hour-and-a-half in a southern Croatian enclave until UN 
officials negotiated their release, a UN spokesman said Thursday. 
  The Canadian peacekeepers were on a patrol with two UN 
military observers -- whose nationality was not specified -- in 
the Medak region, which is under the protection of the UN 
Protection Force in former Yugoslavia (UNPROFOR), when the 
incident took place Tuesday. 
  The Croatian soldiers confronted the six men and fired shots 
into the air to force them to surrender their weapons. They 
were then taken to a Croatian Army post and released only after 
negotiations between local Croatian military officials and the 
local UNPROFOR commanders, the UN source said. 
  A similar incident occured in the Medak pocket on January 5 
when four Canadian UN troops were disarmed and detained for 
several hours by Croatian soldiers. 
  General Jean Cot, the French general who at the time was 
commander of UNPROFOR, protested to Zagreb authorities, calling 
the incident "outrageous." 
  Canada has a battalion of some 600 men in the region. They 
were deployed in Medak in September after the Croatian Army 
launched an offensive there, seizing three Serb vilages and, 
according to UNPROFOR reports, massacring several residents. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30442 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu023_y_94001" </HT>


