<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iranian Foreign Minister Meets With Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Supports Intervention in Bosnia </H4>
<F P=102> AU3101200994 Sofia BTA in English 1921 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Iva Toncheva report] </F>
  [Text] Sofia, January 31 (BTA) -- For nearly an hour and a 
half, Bulgarian Foreign Minister Stanislav Daskalov and his 
Iranian counterpart 'Ali Akbar Velayati who this afternoon 
arrived on a three-day formal visit here, conferred on 
bilateral, regional and international issues. "Bulgaria and 
Iran have traditionally friendly relations," 'Ali Akbar Velayati 
told the press after the meeting. The ministers agreed to 
continue to promote bilateral relations in trade, economy and 
culture. "We firmly believe Bulgaria and Iran can further 
strengthen relations," the Iranian minister also said. 
  Bulgarian Foreign Minister Daskalov said the sides paid 
special attention to economic relations, as lately bilateral 
trade and especially Bulgarian exports have seen a significant 
decline. Bulgaria reaffirmed interest in the construction of a 
transport corridor linking Burgas (on the Southern Bulgarian 
Black Sea coast), Poti (Georgia) and Iran. "We agreed on more 
intensive contacts between the economic ministries," said 
Daskalov. The Iranian delegation includes the first deputy 
minister of trade who will tomorrow hold meetings at the 
ministries of trade, finance, transport and at the Bulgarian 
Chamber of Commerce and Industry. During Velayti's visit the 
sides are expected to sign a Bulgarian-Iranian trade and 
economic Accord. On Wednesday morning Daskalov and Velayati 
will sign a protocol on cooperation between the two foreign 
ministries. 
  Daskalov denied a report in a Tehran newspaper that Velayti 
would raise the issue of announcements that Bulgaria violated 
the Yugoembargo. "We briefed the Iranian side on the Bulgarian 
stance on the Yugoconflict, which is well-known, on Bulgaria's 
relations with its neighbours and on Black Sea economic 
cooperation. The Iranian side reiterated their stand on the war 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina and on relations within their region," 
said the Bulgarian foreign minister. The sides also discussed 
the killing in Sofia last December of four Iranians, two of whom 
illicit drugs dealars, who confronted the police. Two Bulgarian 
police were also killed. "We raised this issue and the two 
sides reaffirmed their interest in clarifying the case. I 
think, the investigation will make things clear," said Daskalov. 
  In response to a question, Velayati reaffirmed the Islamic 
nations' stance in favour of a deployment in Yugoslavia of 
peacemaking troops under UN auspices. "This is our stance taken 
at the meeting in Pakistan, and we've been closely adhering to 
it," said the Iranian foreign minister. 
  'Ali Akbar Velayati tomorrow will be received by President 
Zhelyu Zhelev, Prime Minister Lyuben Berov and National Assembly 
Chairman Aleksandur Yordanov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

