<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on `Special Relationship' With NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202144094 Prague CTK in English 0648 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0202144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington Feb 2 (CTK) -- The Partnership for Peace 
opens up some opportunities, but also leaves a certain 
uncertainty which is consistently exploited by Russia, Chairman 
of the Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee Jiri Payne told 
Czech emigres today. 
  The space between Germany and Russia is to a large extent 
unclear and it is up to Central Europe to settle this, Payne 
said. Russia has also a solution for Central Europe, but we do 
not want to accept it and we are not about to deal with it 
again, Payne stated. 
  In his words, the Czech Republic has a special relationship 
to NATO. None of the post-communist countries can be admitted 
into NATO without the Czechs, Payne said, adding that there was 
no variant whereby the Czech Republic could be ruled out. 
  Russia says it does not want to divide Europe, but its 
policy 
is dividing it, and it is creating spheres of interest by 
defining "close abroad." The Czech Republic, Austria and 
Slovenia are not parts of Russia's "close abroad." This is the 
weightiest argument which singles us out from the Visegrad Four 
(the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland and Hungary), Payne stated. 
  We are cooperating with Slovakia, Poland and Hungary as much 
as possible but we cannot afford to wait for anybody, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

