<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prosecutor Proposes Dissolution of Party </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202173394 Budapest MTI in English 1703 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0202173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 2 Feb (MTI) -- Hungary's Chief Public 
Prosecutor's Office on Wednesday told MTI that, in response to a 
complaint, it had examined the operation of the World National 
Popular Rule Party (WNPRP) for compliance with legal regulations. 
  Investigations showed that the party's aims and activities 
run counter to certain constitutional provisions concerning 
civic rights and freedoms, particularly the right to human 
dignity, minority rights and the equal rights of citizens. 
Also, legal proceedings are under way against the leader and 
another member of the party, on charges of incitement against a 
community. 
  On the basis of the findings of the Chief Public 
Prosecutor's 
Office, the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office has filed a 
petition at the Metropolitan Court to dissolve the party. 
  As previously reported, on January 21 the National Security 
Office lodged a complaint with the National Police Headquarters 
against Albert Szabo, a dual Hungarian/Australian citizen who 
heads the WNPRP, and Akos B., a juvenile activist, for allegedly 
having committed the crime of incitement against a community. 
  The party, registered in October 1993, held a meeting in 
Budapest in mid-January where they denied that the Holocaust had 
ever taken place and defined themselves as successors to the 
Hungarian fascist arrow-cross party and its leader, Ferenc 
Szalasi, who was executed in 1946 for crimes against humanity. 

</TEXT>

