<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polls Show Reaction to `Partnership,' Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302092794 Warsaw PAP in English 1610 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 2 -- One third of the respondents to a 
poll by the Public Opinion Research Centre (CBOS) Wednesday said 
the NATO "Partnership for Peace" proposal creates real chances 
of Poland's joining the Western military alliance, while twenty 
seven percent took the opposite point of view. Forty percent 
either knew nothing or had no opinion on the issue. 
  Fifty five percent of the polled argued that Poland's bid 
for 
NATO is now the best policy for guaranteeing the country's 
security, and according to twenty two percent of the 
respondents, it would be best not to join any military alliances 
and become neutral. Only seven percent claimed that the best 
solution would be to seek a military alliance with other states. 
  Almost half (48 percent) of the CBOS respondents believed 
there is no threat to Poland's independence, while thirty five 
percent stated the opposite. 
  Fifty five percent claim that Russia had objected to Poland 
and other former "socialist block's" efforts to become a NATO 
member because it sought to regain influence over the states, 
one fourth of the polled thought Russia feared that her own 
security will be jeopardized, while every fifth person had no 
opinion on the subject. 
  The survey was conducted on a representative sample of 1,226 
adult Poles on January 14-17. 

</TEXT>

