<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bill Removes Controversial Criminal Code Items </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102160394 Prague CTK in English 1330 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0102160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava Feb 1 (CTK) -- The Slovak Government 
today approved a parliamentary bill that would strike two 
controversial articles from the Criminal Code. Articles 102 and 
103, which were left over from the former Czechoslovak Federal 
Criminal Code, prescribe punishment for defamation of the state 
or its symbols or top representatives. 
  Deputy Premier Roman Kovac, who informed journalists of the 
decision, said the government had based its decision on the 
views of the human rights organisation Amnesty International and 
Slovakia's committee on monitoring the 1975 Helsinki human 
rights agreement. 
  Article 102 is the basis for the current prosecution of Ivan 
Lexa, head of the Government Office and state secretary of the 
Privatisation Ministry, as well as a strong supporter of Premier 
Vladimir Meciar. Lexa made allegedly defamatory remarks about 
President Michal Kovac after Kovac refused to name him minister 
of privatisation. 
  In the Czech Republic, President Vaclav Havel has called 
upon 
the government and the Constitutional Court to abolish or amend 
the two articles. 

</TEXT>

