<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Denies Troops in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302202994 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1900 GMT 
3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302202994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The question of the possible intervention of 
Croatian forces in the Bosnian conflict was the focus of a 
meeting in Zagreb between Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana 
and the Croatian prime minister. Solana ended his visit to 
former Yugoslavia this afternoon. Our special correspondent 
Pedro Fernandez Cespedes reports. 
  [Cespedes] Good evening. Croatian Prime Minister Nikica 
Valentic met Minister Solana and denied the direct intervention 
of regular Croatian troops in the conflict in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The Spanish foreign minister was forceful 
and clear when it came to asking the question in Zagreb at 
midday today. Valentic gave an assurance that it is not the 
case and Javier Solana spoke about a different report. 
  [Begin Solana recording] Whatever the case may be, the 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] forces, the UNPROFOR commanders, 
say that Croatian troops have indeed been seen on the ground. 
[end recording] 
  [Cespedes] A negotiated solution to the problem of 
Srebrenica 
without the need for air strikes is on the way, and hopes of a 
similar -- though more distant -- outcome for the opening of 
Tuzla Airport have not been ruled out. These are the two most 
important pieces of information obtained by Minister Solana 
following his talks with the UN secretary general's 
representative for the military conflict in the former 
Yugoslavia, with whom he agrees that the threats of air strikes 
are bearing fruit. 

</TEXT>

