<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec on Zhirinovskiy Visit, Nuclear Plant </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302173094 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec gave a news 
conference in the Mirror Hall of the Cernin Palace in Prague. 
David Stahlavsky was present on behalf of Czech Radio 
Radiozurnal. 
  [Stahlavsky] [passage omitted] Josef Zieleniec does not 
believe that the visit by Russian nationalist Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy to the Czech Republic is imminent. Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy was invited by the Association for the 
Republic-Republican Party of Czechoslovakia. The minister is 
surprised that Zhirinovskiy, who professed the demise of the 
Czech Republic recently and made improper remarks about our 
country, could have been invited by anyone. He said he found it 
difficult to understand this. 
  The foreign minister responded also to the Austrian effort 
to 
block the American guarantees for the completion of the Temelin 
nuclear power plant [south Bohemia] and to the Vienna 
government's endeavors to stop this construction altogether. 
  [Begin Zieleniec recording] Our course of action is not only 
in line with the law, it is also fair to our neighbors. It is 
neither the fault of our nuclear power plant nor of anyone else 
that Austria has to cope with the preelection situation. Of 
course, we keep in touch with the Austrian Government. We try 
to explain to them that these matters create unnecessary tension 
in our neighborly relations and that there is no need for such a 
spectacular approach. It is a pity. I sincerely regret that 
irrational elements emerge in our relations with Austria. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

