<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy: Security Council Has `Limited Powers' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402112194 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 0900 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402112194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to Karel Kovanda, Czech ambassador to the 
United Nations, who chaired the UN Security Council in January, 
peacekeeping by the United Nations is a question for the distant 
future. 
  Karel Kovanda sees his success and that of Czech foreign 
policy in the Security Council mainly in the fact that the other 
countries view the Czech Republic different from the way they 
did a month ago. Kovanda said that he purposely managed to cut 
down the length of the council's meetings but increased their 
efficiency. 
  He said it is a hard fact of the present world that the 
council has only limited powers that could be further curtailed 
by the decreasing interest of the individual states in 
supporting the council by, for example, being reluctant to offer 
their soldiers for service. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30485 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu024_y_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-024 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Explains Funding </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402115994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1128 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402115994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 4 (TANJUG) -- The Serbian Government 
has announced that industrial producers should receive 200 
million new dinars (equivalent to 200 million deutsche marks) in 
the next two weeks for reviving production which has been at a 
stand-still since international economic sanctions were imposed 
on the country nearly two years ago. The step is just one of 
production-boosting measures envisaged under a programme of 
reconstructing the monetary system and healing the economy of 
Yugoslavia (Serbia/Montenegro). 
  The programme, launched on Janury 24, has already given 
results, curbing what was a world record inflation and improving 
supply on the market. The businessmen warn, however, that funds 
are low for swinging the production cycle anew. The 200 million 
dinars should be paid out of a fund that should be set up for 
financing the economy, one-half of the money to be put up by the 
banks' hard currency reserves, and the balance by the firms by 
selling stock-piles and buying futures. However, not all of 
Serbia's 199,500 firms can hope for a financial injection, but 
only the manufacturers of easily marketable goods, Serbian 
Industry Minister Momir Pavlicevic has told TANJUG. 
  Yugoslavia is implementing its monetary and economic 
recovery 
programme alone, without any outside assistance and in 
conditions of draconic international sanctions, the worst ever 
imposed on any nation, with its firms banned from the world 
markets for both import and export of commodities and fuel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

