<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protest To France Over Ban on Pro-Serb Rally </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402120594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1043 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 4 Feb (TANJUG) -- The Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia has, with 
amazement and bitterness, received reports that the prefecture 
of Le Bas Rhin in France has made a decision to ban the rally 
entitled "24 Hours of Solidarity With the Serbian People," 
scheduled to take place on 6 February. The Ministry's statement 
says that the explanation that "a protest rally against the 
sanctions affecting the Serb community could threaten public 
order due to the risk of counterdemonstrations by associations 
hostile to the Serbs or by those associations whose aims 
contradict those of the rally organizers" is particularly 
surprising. The explanation and other circumstances indicate 
that the competent prefecture could not have made the decision 
without the consent of the French Government. 
  Such measures by the French authorities point to the 
existence of double standards which some countries, and -- 
unfortunately -- France among them, apply to the crisis in the 
former Yugoslavia. The decision to prohibit the Serbs from 
expressing legitimate protest and dissatisfaction against the 
unfounded and genocidal sanctions against the Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia and the Serb people gives even more reason for 
concern, bearing in mind that such measures have never been 
taken against anti-Serb demonstrations in France. 
  The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia, Yugoslav citizens who live and work in France, and 
the entire Yugoslav public, rightly expect that the relevant 
authorities in France will reexamine their decision and enable 
Yugoslav citizens and their French friends to express their 
viewpoint on the sanctions in a peaceful and dignified manner. 
Following the surprising decision by the French authorities the 
Federal Foreign Ministry has ordered the charge d'affaires of 
the Yugoslav Embassy in Paris to lodge a protest note with the 
French Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the statement says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

