<F P=102>  AU0302161194 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0302161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mirza Sadikovic] </F>
  [Text] The Velika Kladusa War Presidency today issued an 
appeal to its citizens, asking [word indistinct] residents and 
members of [Fikret Abdic's] paramilitary formations in 
particular to be sensible and to place themselves under the 
command of the Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina. Velika Kladusa has 
been experiencing unprecedented terror and (?suffering) under 
the veil of [word indistinct] quasi democracy for (?six) months, 
the appeal states. The peace that was established on 12 January 
has only partially helped us to alleviate the consequences of 
Abdic's insane idea. 
  We are most concerned by the fact that our town, your town, 
is now full of foreigners, who are pushing arms into people's 
hands, people who, for their own aims, have caused a fratricidal 
war. The arms that they have pushed into people's hands will 
always be an obstacle to peace and therefore we should listen to 
reason. 
  The appeal further states that Velika Kladusa has been 
burdened by about 2,000 orphans since 3 October last year, 
children whose fathers have been killed. They were forced into 
a struggle for some kind of a quasi state. There are many more 
children in this region who are without fathers. This should be 
a warning to listen to reason and find a peaceful settlement of 
the crisis, the appeal of the Velika Kladusa War Presidency 
states, asking its citizens, particularly members of the 
paramilitary formations, to be sensible and place themselves 
under the command of the Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina by 10 
February of this year. 

</TEXT>

