<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   WFP Warns of Famine Risk Due to Blocked Convoys </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302173794 Paris AFP in English 1657 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Rome, Feb 3 (AFP) -- The number of people threatened 
by famine in Bosnia is rising because of blocked food convoys, 
with only half available supplies getting through, the World 
Food Programme (WFP) warned here Thursday [3 February]. The 
population of central Bosnia is most at risk following delivery 
of only 28 percent of its food needs in December, added the UN 
food relief organisation, which is based here. Airdrops of food 
will be more than trebled to 3,600 tonnes a month to prevent a 
threatened spring shortage caused by the fact that only 65 
percent of needed supplies are in place, the WFP said. 
  Throughout Bosnia, only half the available food aid reaches 
its final destination, the WFP added. Between 20 percent and 30 
percent of children in the Moslem enclave of Maglaj, central 
Bosnia, are suffering from malnutrition, because of a Serb 
blockade of humanitarian relief, it said. Three quarters of the 
food aid required was parachuted in during November and 
December, but it was unknown how much actually reached the 
population, the WFP said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

