<H3> <TI>   Owen Opposes Lifting UN Yugoslav Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0402112094 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1000 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0402112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vanya Manolova on departure of Lord Owen and </F>
Thorvald Stoltenberg from Sofia on 4 January, including recorded 
statement by Owen in response to a correspondent's question -- 
in English fading into Bulgarian translation] 
  [Text] Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, cochairmen of 
the international peace conference on the former Yugoslavia, 
ended their visit to Bulgaria this morning. 
  In a brief statement prior to their departure, Lord Owen 
stressed that it is too early to evaluate the results of their 
tour before they complete their meetings in Tirana and Rome. 
Lord Owen said that it was his general impression that the 
voices of the neighbors of the former Yugoslavia, who are 
suffering serious losses from the Yugoslav embargo, should be 
heard more loudly and clearly. 
  Here is what Lord Owen said when asked by a correspondent 
whether he would support the cancellation of the Yugoslav 
sanctions: 
  [Owen] No, I do not favor lifting the sanctions. At this 
stage, such a step would be premature. Anyway, it is not my job 
to lift them; it is a matter for the UN Security Council. 
However, the sanctions were imposed for a specific purpose, and 
in the final analysis they should serve to achieve this aim. If 
it becomes clear that there is no way that the sanctions will 
bring about a settlement, then indeed it will be necessary to 
raise the question of lifting them. 

</TEXT>

