<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Meciar Comment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302231694 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 2030 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302231694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 2030 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As we have already informed you, the 26th session of 
the National Council was suspended today following the walkout 
of the HZDS [Movement for a Democratic Slovakia] deputies and 
some SNS [Slovak National Party] deputies. Subsequently, the 
opposition deputies were unable to start discussing their 
version of the large-scale privatization law. The parliament 
session might continue on 4 February, following a consultative 
meeting of the parliamentary parties' officials. It is still 
possible that the deputies of the ruling coalition will change 
their decision about not attending the parliament's 
deliberations until a decision is reached by the Constitutional 
Court on whether it was legal to deprive parliament Chairman 
Ivan Gasparovic of the chairmanship of today's session. 
  As HZDS chairman, Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar told TA SR 
[Press Agency of the Slovak Republic] that the Constitution 
clearly defines the powers of the chairman of the National 
Council. Therefore, Meciar considers the vote on whether 
Gasparovic should chair the session to be an informal vote of 
no-confidence in Ivan Gasparovic and an effort to question his 
honor. 
  According to Vladimir Meciar, the initiative of the HZDS 
deputies and some SNS deputies to turn to the Constitutional 
Court is correct. He stressed that the issue was not the 
chairmanship of the session; it was the issue of respecting 
constitutional principles. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

