<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Dismisses `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302234394 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302234394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Milan Cic, chairman of the Slovak Constitutional 
Court, spoke to the Press Agency of the Slovak Republic about 
his stand on today's events in parliament. He said that his 
post as chairman of the Constitutional Court does not give him 
the right to interpret the Constitution on his own. However, he 
perceives the entire problem as predominantly a political 
conflict. Therefore, it should be tackled using political means 
and forms--first at a session of the cross-party standing 
committee chaired by the chairman, at meetings of deputies' 
clubs, through the cooperation of the clubs chairmen, at the 
level of committees and political bodies--and only if this fails 
should the issue be presented to a plenary session [of 
parliament] or, if need be, to the Constitutional Court. 
  Milan Cic does not perceive the current situation in 
parliament as a parliamentary crisis or even a constitutional 
crisis. It is a misunderstanding that can be overcome provided 
there is goodwill, the chairman of the Constitutional Court 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

