<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: Over 50% Believe Living Standard Lower </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302175894 Bratislava REPUBLIKA in Slovak 2 Feb 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302175894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava REPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "Public Opinion in Statistical Figures"] </F>
  [Text] Bratislava--In opinion polls conducted by the 
Slovak Statistical Office in December 1993, a total of 13 
percent of the respondents said that their standard of living 
was better than in the same period in 1992. Compared with the 
results obtained in September 1992, when 10 percent said the 
standard of living had improved, this is a slightly positive 
trend. A total of 29 percent of respondents said in December 
1993 that their standard of living did not change--32 percent of 
respondents responded the same in September 1992. In both 
cases, 58 percent of respondents described their standard of 
living as deteriorating. 
  The polls have shown that people view the standard of living 
depending on political preferences, education, and membership in 
social and professional groups. There was a relatively higher 
percentage of respondents who said that their standard of living 
was improving in the group of sympathizers with the Movement for 
Democratic Slovakia sympathizers (25 percent) and the Slovak 
National Party (18 percent). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

