<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak, Borowski, Kwasniewski Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402104494 Warsaw Third Program Radio Network in Polish 
0900 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Third Program Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak, Deputy Prime 
Minister Marek Borowski, and Aleksander Kwasniewski, leader of 
the Social Democracy of the Polish Republic last night discussed 
reaching a new coalition agreement. We were told this by 
today's guest, Aleksander Kwasniewski. Later today the leaders 
of the Polish Peasant Party and the Democratic Left Alliance 
will meet. 
  [Begin recording] [Kwasniewski] I am trying to convince both 
Marek Borowski and the prime minister about the hierarchy of 
issues. The most important issue for today is the budget; the 
most important issue is an effective government; personal 
matters are somewhere behind. I am convinced that if such 
principles are accepted by the prime minister then Marek 
Borowski will not submit his resignation--he is a responsible 
politician.... 
  [Unidentified correspondent, interrupts] But did he say 
yesterday that he was withdrawing his resignation? 
  [Kwasniewski] The resignation has not been submitted... 
  [Correspondent, interrupting] It was submitted last Friday. 
  [Kwasniewski] No, it was not submitted; it was just 
announced... 
  [Correspondent, interrupting] Then did he withdraw his 
announcement? 
  [Kwasniewski] Yes, if these principles are accepted then I 
think that the whole issue will be settled positively. [end 
recording] 
  Kwasniewski added that he expects Prime minister Waldemar 
Pawlak's reply on the question of possible nominations for 
deputy ministers of defense, foreign affairs and internal 
affairs from among the coalition members. The prime minister 
will also explain the role of Jerzy Milewski, deputy defense 
minister and the head of the National Security Office, in the 
government. 

</TEXT>

