<H3> <TI>   SLD Leader Stresses Coalition Not Threatened </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402104094 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 0900 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Aleksander Kwasniewski, leader of the Democratic 
Left Alliance [SLD] has given an assurance that the existence of 
the government coalition is not threatened at present. In a 
statement for the Signals of the Day, the early morning slot of 
the Polish Radio first program, Aleksander Kwasniewski said that 
there was no possibility at present to replace the coalition of 
the PSL [Polish Peasant Party] and the SLD with any other 
political alliance. 
  Kwasniewski said that his talks yesterday with Prime 
Minister 
Waldemar Pawlak focused, among other things, on making the 
government activities more effective. Talks on the issue are to 
continue today, and, according to Aleksander Kwasniewski, they 
are going in the right direction. 
  In Kwasniewski's view, Minister of Finance Marek Borowski 
will certainly not resign. 

</TEXT>

