<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shelling of Sarajevo Market Kills Dozens </TI></H3>
<H4>   Serbs Doubt Massacre Report </H4>
<F P=102> LD0602120894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1115 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602120894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zvornik, Feb 6 (TANJUG) -- The Serb side has strong 
reasons for doubting the objectivity and veracity of the 
official report on the latest civilian deaths caused by a mortar 
exlosion at a crowded Sarajevo market on Saturday, the Bosnian 
Serb Army commander, Major General Manojlo Milovanovic, told 
TANJUG on Sunday [6 February]. This comes after the U.N. 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR) had `unfoundedly and 
unsubstantiatedly blamed the Serb side, without coming up with 
any material evidence,' for Friday's mortar attack which killed 
nine people in a food queue in Sarajevo's Dobrinja suburb, Gen. 
Milovanovic said. 
  In order to prevent similar moves, the Serb side on Saturday 
proposed that a joint committee, made up of military experts of 
the UNPROFOR, the Bosnian Serbs and Muslims, visits the scene of 
the attack together with the military commanders of the Bosnian 
Serbs, Muslims and the UNPROFOR. The Muslims immediately 
refused to allow its experts to go to the scene of the explosion 
as did UNPROFOR chief-of-staff for Bosnia, General Angus Ramsey, 
although he had first accepted this proposal, Gen. Milovanovic 
said. 
  According to him, all this gives much reason to the Serb 
side 
to doubt the objectivity and truthfullness of the report on the 
blast at the Sarajevo market which killed 66 people and wounded 
close to 200. Gen. Milovanovic recalled that at the eve of all 
previous major peace talks, the Muslims had orchestrated even 
the killings of civilians in order to blame the Serbs for 
everything and cause the internationalization of the war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30549 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu025_i_94007" </HT>


