<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shelling of Sarajevo Market Kills Dozens </TI></H3>
<H4>   Rose: Responsible Side Unknown </H4>
<F P=102> LD0602162894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1619 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602162894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 6 (TANJUG) -- U.N. Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) Commander for Bosnia-Herzegovina, General Michael 
Rose on Sunday said that analysis had been completed but it was 
impossible to say which of the warring sides had on Saturday 
fired a mortar shell on an open air market in Sarajevo, killing 
68 people and wounding nearly 200. REUTER said that General 
Rose had visited the market on Sunday together with UNPROFOR 
Commander for the former Yugoslavia, Gen. Jean Cot, and civilian 
head of UNPROFOR Yasushi Akashi to inspect `the mortar crater 
and surrounding shrapnel holes.' The UNPROFOR officials were 
accompanied by Sarajevo's Muslim Mayor Muhamed Kresevljakovic 
and Bosnian Muslim Interior Minister Bakir Alispahic. Akashi 
was quoted by the AFP as saying there were some suspicions but 
it could not be said with certainty who was responsible for the 
tragedy. 
  The Bosnian Serbs on Saturday categorically rejected the 
Bosnian Muslim accusations that Bosnian Serb troops were 
responsible for the crime, and it called for an urgent 
investigation to be carried out by a joint commission of 
representatives of UNPROFOR, the Bosnian Serb and the Muslim 
sides. The proposal was turned down by the Muslims. 
  After visiting the market in Sarajevo, Akashi and General 
Cot 
went to meet with the Bosnian Muslim presidency, according to 
the AFP. The two officials are to leave Sarajevo on Sunday 
afternoon, according to the same source. Representative of the 
office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Sergio 
Mele on Sunday said the evacuation of the wounded had begun. 
  Mele said that U.N. armoured personnel carriers were being 
used to take the wounded from city hospitals to the airport. He 
said 58 wounded were expected to be evacuated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

