<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shelling of Sarajevo Market Kills Dozens </TI></H3>
<H4>   Wounded To Be Evacuated </H4>
<F P=102> AU0702120394 Paris AFP in English 1150 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0702120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Feb 7 (AFP) -- Sixteen people wounded by a 
shell that crashed into a Sarajevo market over the weekend were 
to be evacuated to hospitals in Italy and Germany on Monday [7 
February], UNHCR [United Nations High Commissioner for Regugees] 
medical coordinator Genevieve Begkoyian said. She said the 
victims, among some 200 people injured by the Saturday blast 
that also killed 68, would be transported to Ancona, Italy, 
where officials have offered 10 hospital beds. The remainder 
would be transported to American hospitals in Germany. 
  On Sunday, 50 wounded people and 74 family members were 
evacuated from the Bosnian capital. Among the wounded were 24 
people injured in the market blast and a similar attack on a 
food line on Friday. The rest of the injured had been on a 
waiting list for evacuation. Begkoyian said only mothers of the 
victims were allowed to accompany them as their fathers must 
fulfill their military obligation. She said 96 of those wounded 
by the market attack are being treated at the city's Kosevo 
hospital and 31 others are at the French hospital. She said 
those slightly injured by the blast have been sent home and many 
have been amputated. 
  Begkoyian said the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) 
is also seeking to evacuate 160 additional patients from 
Sarajevo, most of them suffering from kidney problems. 
  In Germany, a spokeswoman at the the Ramstein US airbase 
near 
Kaiserslautern said the victims were expected to arrive around 
6:00 p.m. (1700 GMT). According to a spokesman at the Frankfurt 
airbase handling humanitarian aid to Bosnia, among those due to 
arrive would be between 12 and 20 stretcher cases. 
  Sunday evening three planeloads of Sarajevo wounded and 
their 
relatives arrived at Ramstein. They comprised 35 stretcher 
cases, 15 walking wounded and 79 relatives, the spokeswoman 
said. The wounded were taken to the US hospital at Landstuhl 
near Ramstein. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

