<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Collapse </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602215294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2143 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602215294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 6 (TANJUG) -- Chief of the U.N. 
operation in former Yugoslavia Yakushi Akashi has said that 
U.N.-mediated talks on a truce between Bosnia's Serbs and 
Moslems collapsed on Sunday [6 February]. REUTERS quoted Akashi 
as saying he had tried to mediate and effect a total and 
immediate ceasefire, but that vast differences existed between 
the conditions made by the two confronted sides. He regretted 
that no agreement had resulted at this time, but refused to 
attribute responsibility to either side. 
  The Japanese diplomat added that the biggest obstacle to an 
agreement was the Moslems' insistence that the Serbs withdraw 
their artillery from positions around Sarajevo and place it 
under U.N. control. Akashi and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic had drafted a truce agreement at their meeting earlier 
in the day. The truce, subject to Moslem approval on Sunday 
evening, was to take effect at 10 A.M. local time (09:00 G.M.T.) 
on Monday, February 7. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

