<H3> <TI>   Rifkind, Silajdzic Statements Following Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602190694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0602190694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Malcolm Rifkind, the defense minister 
[title as received] of Great Britain, visited Sarajevo today. 
The guest from Britain conveyed his government's deep concern 
for the situation in Sarajevo and the whole of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Edin Nusic has the report. 
  [Nusic] Malcolm Rifkind and [Bosnian Prime Minister] Haris 
Silajdzic gave statements following the talks. The British 
defense minister conveyed the concern of the British Government 
for the situation in Sarajevo, and added: 
  [Begin Rifkind recording, in English, fading to superimposed 
Serbo-Croatian translation] I think that the whole world was 
struck by the horror that befell the citizens of Sarajevo. 
  Although this is the most serious incident, we believe that 
it is by no means the only one. The citizens of Sarajevo have 
for a long time faced fatal agony and fear. We must consider 
every possibility of improving the situation and restoring peace 
to Sarajevo and the whole of Bosnia-Herzegovina as soon as 
possible. [end recording] 
  [Nusic] Prime Minister Silajdzic had the following to say 
about his talks with the British defense minister: 
  [Begin Silajdzic recording] The visit by Mr. Rifkind, the 
defense minister of Great Britain, shows Great Britain's current 
new interest in Bosnia-Herzegovina. I tried to explain our 
situation concerning humanitarian aid and in the field. 
Humanitarian problems are huge, and they must not be forgotten 
under the circumstances, although it is very difficult to speak 
about humanitarian convoys after 66 deaths and 196 injuries 
yesterday. We said that we believe that force should be used 
against those who stop humanitarian convoys and, of course, 
against those who kill civilians in the way that it was done 
yesterday. We said that we have been waging a war against 
fascism on our own for two years now, and that Europe surprised 
us. Fascism is an issue that concerns all of us, something we 
all must fight. I hope that after this visit, which is well 
timed, this will no longer be so. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

