<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croats Attack Krajina Defense Lines </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602162094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1516 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Knin, Feb 6 (TANJUG) -- Croatian forces on Sunday 
resumed attacks on Serb defence lines in the north Dalmatian 
front, the Bosnian Serb command said on Sunday [6 February]. 
Intensive mortar, cannon and tank fire was opened on the region 
of Smiljcici, Kasici (west of Benkovac) and on the villages in 
the Novigrad hinterland. The attacks wounded one Serb soldier, 
and inflicted considerable material damage on civilian targets, 
thus forcing the Serb troops to respond. 
  The Croatian forces also staged provocative attacks on the 
Skradin hinterland, the Drnis front and the area of Plasko in 
Lika while, in the other parts of the front, the warring sides 
observed the ceasefire. The Croatians launched offensive 
actions despite the Christmas ceasefire, which was agreed late 
last year and extended on two occasions. It remains in force 
until February 28. The republic of Serb Krajina (R.S.K.) was 
proclaimed a U.N. protected area (UNPA) and, under the Vance 
plan, 14,000 U.N. peacekeepers were sent there in early 1992. 
The plan called for an end to the fighting between Croatian 
army and the local Serbs. R.S.K. was proclaimed by the local 
Serbs in territories where they are in the majority in response 
to Croatia's forcible secession from the former Yugoslav 
federation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

