<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatian UN Envoy Explains Statement on Attack </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402232294 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 2220 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402232294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] We telephoned Mario Nobilo [in New York] 
this evening and asked him to explain his alleged statement 
regarding an attack on Serbs in the occupied Croatian 
territories in case sanctions are introduced [against Croatia]. 
May we just warn that this statement orbited the entire world 
via REUTERS and caused considerable concern among the 
international public. Here is the explanation of our UN 
ambassador: 
  [Begin Nobilo recording] The threat that Croatia will 
declare 
war against Krajina if sanctions are introduced was simplified 
and taken out of context. Journalists insisted on knowing what 
would happen if sanctions were to be introduced. My opinion is 
that sanctions would move Croatia and the entire region closer 
to war. Apart from this, they would create a new wave of 
refugees throughout Europe, and disturb the balance of forces 
because Serbs would then be in a more favorable position with 
all the unforeseeable consequences this would entail. Croatia, 
as the victim of aggression, would find it difficult to accept 
sanctions as far as its morale is concerned. 
  In any case, both the Bosnian ambassador and I are trying to 
place this whole new situation within the context of successful 
talks expected at the next round of Croatian-Muslim talks on the 
settlement of the remaining controversial matters. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

