<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Prime Minister Borowski Tenders Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402172994 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1700 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Marek Borowski, deputy prime minister and minister 
of finance, has tendered his resignation from the post he holds. 
This ensued after the prime minister did not accept the proposal 
of the deputy prime minister regarding, above all, a clear 
outline of the division of prerogatives within the government. 
  Marek Borowski, justifying his decision, said that the 
so-called Deputy Finance Stefan Kawalec affair ought to be seen 
in a wider context, which is made up of many statements by the 
prime minister. In the view of Marek Borowski, they undermine 
his activity as deputy prime minister. Marek Borowski viewed 
the statements of the prime minister as a particular vote of no 
confidence. 
  We still do not know if Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak has 
accepted Marek Borowski's resignation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

