<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conflict Could Cause Coalition Split </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402232994 Warsaw Third Program Radio Network in Polish 
2200 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402232994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Third Program Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] After a meeting with ministers from the 
Democratic Left Alliance [SLD], the Sejm speaker, Jozef Oleksy, 
declared that he did not exclude a breakup of the coalition. 
  Monika Olejnik has just returned from the Sejm: 
  [Olejnik] Certain ministers who took part in this discussion 
are also of the opinion that a breakup of the coalition is 
possible. The majority of them say that Prime Minister Waldemar 
Pawlak will accept Marek Borowski's resignation. Some say that, 
despite everything, the coalition will survive. Aleksander 
Kwasniewski told journalists that there was already a new name, 
but he said this half in jest, half seriously. However, quite 
seriously, Marek Borowski said: 
  [Begin recording] [Borowski] I will certainly not gather up 
my belongings and will not go home because there are tasks to be 
fulfilled. 
  [Olejnik] Does the Parliamentary Floor Group bear you a 
grudge for resigning, or does it accept your arguments? 
  [Borowski] I think it accepts them. The group that debated 
[the situation] agreed that these were conditions that could be 
accepted. 
  [Olejnik] Mr. [Deputy] Prime Minister, do you not think it 
egoistic? You are resigning; this is a threat to the SLD 
coalition with the Polish Peasant Party [PSL]. Do you not 
exclude the possibility that this could be a threat? 
  [Borowski] If certain trends are developing the wrong way, 
there remains only the question of when one should do it [as 
heard]--whether to wait until it becomes difficult to patch up 
anything or whether to do it earlier. I came to the conclusion 
that earlier is better. There may have been those who thought 
it would have been better to wait. [end recording] 
  [Olejnik] Marek Borowski told journalists that the 
conditions 
set by the SLD were the conditions of all of the ministers who 
belong to the SLD. The SLD was waiting all the time for a 
telephone call from Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak. It is not 
known whether this will happen tomorrow, the day after, or the 
day after that. 

</TEXT>

