<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Reacts to Complaint About Dukovany Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402202894 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 0800 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] It is the duty of the Czech Republic to insure the 
safety standards of the nuclear power industry on its territory, 
and Austria has neither the right nor the duty to intervene in 
this matter. This was the indirect reaction of Vladimir Dlouhy, 
minister of trade and industry, to claims made by Peter 
Rosenstingl, the Austrian Freedom Party spokesman, that the 
Czech nuclear power industry was becoming an ever-more-serious 
safety hazard for the whole of Europe. 
  According to Minister Dlouhy, the causes of the fire at the 
Dukovany nuclear power station were of a routine nature and 
therefore should not be interpreted as evidence of the Czech 
Republic's obsolete technology and its failure to insure nuclear 
safety. Such a breakdown could happen anywhere. The fact that 
it has happened just now is rather unpleasant, added Vladimir 
Dlouhy. 

</TEXT>

