<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Independent Commercial TV Station Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602105194 Bratislava STV 1 Television Network in Slovak 
1830 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0602105194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava STV 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] The first national commercial 
television station in the postsocialist countries is Nova, a 
Czech independent television company. You may be interested in 
the fact that the name Nova was chosen by a lady living in 
Bratislava. 
  The license was awarded by the Radio and Television 
Broadcasting Council of the Czech Republic on 30 January 1993, 
and the deadline for starting the broadcast was yesterday [4 
February]. Nova is ambitious: It will broadcast on average 19 
hours a day, using the former F1 [federal television] channel. 
It will broadcast newsreels and current affairs programs, some 
documentaries, and entertainment and musical programs. To begin 
with, it owns broadcasting rights for more than 400 foreign 
films, which will be broadcast dubbed. Nova will use the 
opportunity to insert advertisements during film screenings, but 
only with the approval of the films' authors. Also, much is 
expected from daily morning programs. 
  An interesting program feature is a vox populi, a sort of 
television Hyde Park. In the Krone department store [in 
Prague], there is a television cabin where, for a fee of 10 
[Czech] korunas, you can record any message you wish. [passage 
omitted] 
  According to Vladimir Zelezny, the Nova director general, 
the 
viewers are expected to be average Czech citizens. There are no 
unnecessarily high expectations about their viewers, but they 
are not being underestimated, either. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

