<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgrade Protests Damage to Hamburg Consulate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602201194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1952 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 6 (TANJUG) -- The Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia Foreign Ministry on Sunday lodged a sharp protest 
with the charge d'affaires of the German embassy in Belgrade in 
connection with the vandalizing of the building of the Yugoslav 
consulate general in Hamburg in violent demonstrations staged by 
Bosnian Muslims. Militant Bosnian Muslims organized the 
demonstrations without permission from local authorities, and 
stoned the building, breaking windows and damaging doors on it. 
  Ambassador in the Yugoslav Foreign Ministry Zivadin 
Jovanovic 
said that the unprovoked demonstrations were violent, and the 
German side was responsible for the damages caused on the 
consulate building, the property of Yugoslavia. Ambassador 
Jovanovic requested of German authorities to open a thorough 
investigation, take adequate measures against the perpetrators 
of the violence, and secure all necessary conditions for the 
normal work and full security of the Yugoslav diplomatic and 
consular missions and representatives in Germany. 
  Charge d'affaires of the German embassy in Belgrade Gerhard 
Schwemgens said he regretted the deplorable incident, and 
promised he would communicate the Yugoslav protest to his 
government so that similar incidents would be prevented in 
future. 

</TEXT>

