<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Milosevic Discusses Bosnia With Stoltenberg, Owen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702121394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1124 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 7 Feb (TANJUG) -- This morning President 
of the Republic of Serbia Slobodan Milosevic received Thorvald 
Stoltenberg and David Owen, the cochairmen of the Geneva 
conference. As the Serbian president's office has announced, 
they discussed the creation of conditions for restoring peace in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina as soon as possible and the stabilization of 
the overall situation in the Yugoslav area. It was noted that 
the negotiating process has no alternative as the path toward 
peace, and that it should not be allowed to suspend the 
negotiations before a final peace agreement is reached. 
  They stressed the close link between lifting the sanctions 
against Serbia, that is, the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and 
finding a peaceful solution to Bosnia-Herzegovina, and pointed 
to the forces still opposed to this. They also discussed the 
efforts for an overall normalization of relations in the 
Yugoslav area, and decided that the normalization of relations 
between Serbs and Croats is of great importance in that context. 
  Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic also took part 
in the talks. 

</TEXT>

