<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Debates SDS No-Confidence Motion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0502151694 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0502151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mariya Tsankova] </F>
  [Text] Today's plenary session of the National Assembly 
was extended to allow the deputies to debate the motion for a no 
confidence vote in Lyuben Berov's cabinet proposed by the 
parliamentary group of the SDS [Union of Democratic Forces]. 
The proposers of the motion argued that the government was to 
blame for failing to bring the crime rate under control and to 
act against the growth of organized crime. The Socialist 
deputies did not [word indistinct] their criticisms of the Berov 
cabinet, but called for the drafting of a national program to 
combat crime. The National Assembly deputies of the New 
Alliance for Democracy gave the government and the Interior 
Ministry leadership a one-month deadline to conduct a purge at 
all levels within the Interior Ministry to remove corrupt 
officials. 
  The actual vote on the no-confidence motion will be held by 
secret ballot next Wednesday [9 February]. On Tuesday [8 
February] the National Assembly will hold an extraordinary 
plenary session, at which the deputies are likely to debate the 
state budget bill, the excise bill, the draft law on aliens' 
residence in Bulgaria, and the draft law on the National 
Security Service. 

</TEXT>

