<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Assesses CSCE Vienna Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302203394 Sofia BTA in English 1907 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, February 3 (BTA) -- A Bulgarian delegation, 
led by Deputy Foreign Minister Todor Churov, attended a meeting 
in Vienna of the Conference on Security and Cooperation in 
Europe. The need of a transport and communications 
infrastructure skirting the territory of the former Yugoslavia 
was on the agenda. The Bulgarian delegation returned from Vienna 
today. 
  According to Mr. Churov the meeting was a success, at least 
in the short term. "In a longer-term prospect, things are a 
little bit more complicated because funding is involved," he 
said. 
  "Still, I think that the Bulgarian priorities were accepted 
at the meeting," the deputy foreign minister said. The 
Bulgarian projects concerning the overloaded border crossings, 
could be arranged in nine to twelve months time, as Mr. Churov 
put it. "As to our longer-term proposals, it all depends on what 
the EU members of the G-24 will decide, and specifically whether 
funding will be provided within a reasonable period of three to 
five years." 

</TEXT>

