<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec Signs Partnership for Peace Materials </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302184394 Prague CTK in English 1733 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302184394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Feb 3 (CTK) -- Czech Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec put his signature on materials concerning the Czech 
Republic's membership in the Partnership for Peace project, he 
said at a press conference today. 
  The materials will be submitted to the government, which is 
to discuss them on Wednesday [9 February], Zieleniec said. 
  According to the Czech Constitution, parliamentary approval 
is not necessary for the Czech Republic to join the Partnership 
for Peace, Zieleniec said. After the government gives its 
approval, either Premier Vaclav Klaus or Zieleniec himself will 
sign the general declaration on joining the project. 
  The Partnership for Peace programme, which was approved by 
NATO member countries on January 10, 1994 in Brussels, envisages 
military cooperation with the countries of Eastern and Central 
Europe and their eventual admission to the Alliance. 
  Zieleniec said that after signing the document he would 
oversee the Czech Republic's special proposal for specific 
cooperation with the Alliance and that NATO would also draw up 
similar materials concerning this cooperation. These two 
documents will then form the basis of the agreement between the 
Czech Republic and NATO on the Partnership for Peace. 
  While under the Partnership for Peace, Czech soldiers could 
eventually be sent abroad, Zieleniec said that the Czech 
Constitution requires parliamentary approval of sending armed 
forces outside of Czech territory. Therefore, "some adjustments 
will be necessary" to the regulations, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

