<H3> <TI>   Dispute With Austria Over Nuclear Plant Cited </TI></H3>
<H4>   IAEA Informed About Fire </H4>
<F P=102> AU0402105094 Prague CTK in English 2254 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0402105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, Feb 3 (CTK) -- Czech officials informed the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) this afternoon about 
the fire that broke out at the Dukovany nuclear power plant this 
morning, IAEA spokesman Hans-Friedrich Meyer said today. 
  Meyer said that the fire, which occurred in one of the 
transformers in the plant's third bloc, was completely 
extinguished in two hours and did not cause any leak of 
radioactive materials. The fire rated a zero on the INES 
International Nuclear Safety Scale. 
  The Austrian environmental organization Global 2000, 
however, 
announced that Czech environmentalists from the Duha (Rainbow) 
movement had informed them that the accident rated a three on 
the INES scale. The environmentalists said that a secondary 
cooling system had been damaged, causing a radioactive leak. 
Local residents were warned by siren and doses of iodine were 
distributed, the group said. 

</TEXT>

