<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaves for Visit to India, Thailand </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0702133394 Prague CTK in English 1503 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0702133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 6 (CTk) -- Czech President Vaclav Havel 
today left for an eight-day tour of India and Thailand, 
accompanied by Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec, Finance 
Minister Ivan Kocarnik and Deputy Industry and Trade Minister 
Radomir Sabela. 
  In Delhi Havel will meet Indian President Shankar Dayal 
Sharma, at whose invitation the visit takes place and Indian 
Premier Narasimh P. V. Rao. He will also travel to Varanasi and 
Calcutta, where he will visit Mother Theresa's mission. 
  On February 11 Havel will visit Thailand at the invitation 
of 
the king of Thailand, Phumiphon Adunyadet. Besides meeting the 
king, Havel will meet Thai Premier Chuan Likphai and Chairman of 
Parliament Marut Benneg. 
  This is Havel's second trip to Asia which he visited in 
April 
1992 in his capacity as Czechoslovak president. He went then to 
Japan and South Korea and on his way back home he made a short 
stop-over in India. 
  "One of the goals of my current visit to Asia is to 
emphasize 
the Czech Republic's membership in the United Nations Security 
Council and our share of responsibility for world developments 
ensuing from this membership. We also want to point out that 
also far distant countries are very important for the Czech 
Republic," Havel said before his departure. 

</TEXT>

