<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak on Importance of Business With Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302201394 Warsaw PAP in English 1800 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Feb. 3 -- We want to do business with 
Western European countries which will benefit both sides, Prime 
Minister Waldemar Pawlak told his audience here Thursday 
addressing an international conference devoted to Poland. 
  The conference, organized by the Washington-based Centre for 
International and Strategic Studies, was attended by the German 
Minister of Defence Volker Ruehe, Member of the European 
Commission Sir Leon Brittan, representatives of Polish political 
and economic circles, including Jan Krzysztof Bielecki, Hanna 
Gronkiewicz-Waltz, Janusz Lewandowski, Janusz Onyszkiewicz, and 
many other Polish and West European politicians and businessmen. 
  Pawlak said that trade concessions offered Poland by Western 
European nations were fine in theory but that in practice 
enormous administrative and bureaucratic obstacles remained. He 
declared a staunch defence of the Polish interests and 
reiterated the firm will of Poland to fully integrate with the 
European Union. 
  The Prime Minister spoke in high terms of the Polish 
economic 
situation, mentioning this year's targets of 4.5 percent growth 
in the GDP and an inflation rate of ca. 25 per cent. But he 
said the days of easy profits from investments in Poland were 
over and that his government was now looking "to do business 
which is good for both sides." 

</TEXT>

