<H3> <TI>   SLD Head To Meet With Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302221594 Warsaw PAP in English 1920 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0302221594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb 3 -- The leader of the Democratic Left 
alliance (SLD) Aleksander Kwasniewski told a press conference 
here Thursday he would meet Prime Minister Pawlak Thursday night 
to discuss not just the dismissal of vice-minister of finance 
but also more fundamental problems of governing the country. 
  Kwasniewski said that "there are serious problems which 
should not be underrated," but declined to give a clear cut 
answer to reporters' questions about the possible resignation of 
Vice-Premier and Finance Minister Marek Borowski. 
  The leader of SLD declared that "it would certainly be the 
worst way out if we provoked a major rift within the ruling 
coalition or a political conflict on a national scale" and added 
that there were numerous possibilities of avoiding such a 
scenario. 
  According to Kwasniewski, neither his alliance nor the 
Polish 
Peasant Party (PSL) of Prime Minister pawlak had at the present 
time any alternative to the current coalition arrangment. What 
was needed was a better coordination of their activities. 
  Referring to the expected topics of his Thursday night 
meeting with Pawlak, Kwasniewski said he wanted to discuss not 
only the style and manners of making politics but a few 
fundamental questions as well. They were the mode of operation 
of the government and economic concepts. 
  In this connection Kwasniewski spoke critically about 
opinions on economic issues voiced recently by PSL politicians 
such as the minister for foreign economic cooperation, the 
chairman of the Sejm Privatization Committee and the prime 
minister. 

</TEXT>

