<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Cited on Lifting Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702192894 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1700 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] We begin our reports with developments 
in the Yugoslav crisis at home and abroad. [Hungarian Foreign 
Minister] Geza Jeszenszky, who visited Serbia a few days ago, 
talked about the Yugoslav situation this afternoon at a news 
conference. Miklos Lengyel reports: 
  [Lengyel] Hungary supports the lifting of sanctions against 
the rump Yugoslavia only if Belgrade meets international 
expectations, Geza Jeszenszky emphasized at his press briefing 
today. The Hungarian foreign minister said that pressure on the 
Hungarian minority in Serbia had eased. Hungary was striving 
for balanced relations with all successor states to Yugoslavia. 
  The Hungarian foreign minister also plans to visit Zagreb 
and 
Sarajevo soon. Geza Jeszenszky thinks there is still a chance 
of finding some sort of peace solution in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  However, Geza Jeszenszky considered it regrettable that 
Istvan Szentivanyi, an Alliance of Free Democrats deputy, had 
criticized the foreign minister's Belgrade talks. He was 
surprised that THE WASHINGTON POST had only belatedly commented 
on his visit to Belgrade. He denied that the Hungarian 
Government had only now mentioned the detrimental effects of the 
sanctions on Hungary. If the sanctions did not work properly, 
it was not Hungary's fault, Geza Jeszenszky said. 

</TEXT>

