<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civic Alliance Warns About Media Control </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0702183594 Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA in Romanian 3 Feb 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> AU0702183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by the Civic Alliance; place and date not given: </F>
"Recent Amendments"] 
  [Text] The Civic Alliance and the Association for Free and 
Correct Information via Radio and Television draw attention to 
the executive power's attempt to legally place the public 
audiovisual media under its jurisdiction. 
  The introduction, at the last moment, of a set of amendments 
by the parliamentary group of the Social Democracy Party of 
Romania [PDSR], after the draft bill had been worked on for a 
long time by the specialized commission of the Chamber of 
Deputies, testifies to an attempt to either delay the 
legislation process or (if the amendments would be accepted by 
the plenary session of the Chamber of Deputies) to the desire to 
totally and effectively acquire these two public services -- 
radio and television. 
  Not only because of certain provisions that limit the 
independence of the radio and television and their staff but 
also through procedures proposed for the appointment of the 
Consultative Council, the Management Boards and their chairmen 
(by the government and the presidency respectively), the PDSR 
amendments violate the principles stipulated by any democratic 
audio-visual law, including the recommendations made to our 
country by the Council of Europe. 
  Bucharest, 2 February 1994 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

