<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Expects Serbs To `Test Europe' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702230294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2100 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702230294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Alija Izetbegovic, the president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, gave a statement to Sarajevo 
Radio and TV reporters following [UN Secretary General Butrus] 
Butrus-Ghali's request to NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner 
on the authorization of air attacks against the Serb aggressor's 
positions. 
  [Begin Izetbegovic recording] I believe that this is a 
request to prepare for such an action, to authorize the command 
of NATO's Sector South to carry out the attacks, but -- and this 
is important -- at the UN request. This means that Butrus-Ghali 
will have to order it once again. This is typical of 
Butrus-Ghali's manner. 
  But, I hear that this is obviously being seriously 
discussed. 
It is becoming a serious issue. As you know, we held talks 
with [UN envoy] Akashi yesterday. He then held talks with the 
Serb side. We demanded -- to avoid the air attacks but achieve 
the goal at the same time -- that the Serbs, of their own free 
will, withdraw their artillery and place it under UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] control. This was our latest demand. They 
issued some counterproposal or other -- for the artillery to be 
just monitored -- that we obviously rejected. 
  We increased the pressure today by sending another letter to 
the [European] Twelve, who have just begun a session, and to the 
NATO secretary general -- they are holding a session tomorrow. 
  Something seems to be moving in the European Union. I heard 
that the European Union has made a decision to break the siege 
of the city, if necessary with the use of force. So, obviously, 
things are moving in some direction. There is at least a 50-50 
chance that NATO attacks against those positions will 
materialize. 
  I believe that the Serbs will take the risk. They will try 
to test Europe, to see if it will do it or not, for their 
experience with Europe so far has shown that Europe is 
indecisive. I think they will play that card. I would not say 
that they will withdraw of their own [free] will. Something has 
changed, but we have paid for it. The price was those 70 lives 
and 200 wounded, for people to realize that such absurdity and 
evil cannot be tolerated any more. Or they understood that this 
is not only the question of Bosnia- Herzegovina, that this is -- 
as our esteemed visitor from Pakistan [Benazir Bhutto] said -- 
that this is a moral issue, which concerns every man. Can crime 
be tolerated and is it not encouragement for crime and fascism, 
opening the doors wide for them in the world? You see, there 
are some new, sad phenomena in Russia, which really pose a 
threat to the world, to the survival of the world. If we look 
back perhaps we could trace it to the lax attitude and tolerance 
in Europe toward an evil that appeared in the Balkans some four 
or five years ago. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30724 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu026_i_94004" </HT>


